WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:19.150 --> 00:00:21.400
&gt;&gt; Hello, everyone.

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:22.960
My name is Betsy Peterson.

00:00:22.960 --> 00:00:26.230
I'm the Director of the American
Folklife Center here at the Library

00:00:26.230 --> 00:00:28.130
of Congress, and on
behalf of the staff,

00:00:28.130 --> 00:00:30.200
I want to welcome you all today.

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:33.460
It's a gorgeous day here,
and I'm really pleased

00:00:33.460 --> 00:00:37.160
that you all are here
to share it with us.

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:42.920
This is a special program, part
of our Homegrown Concert Series,

00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:49.470
part of our Lecture Series, and
it's an opportunity for us to have,

00:00:49.470 --> 00:00:54.400
for us to engage in a
conversation with individuals

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:57.730
who have been awarded the
National Heritage Fellowship,

00:00:57.730 --> 00:01:01.390
which is the highest honor
given to traditional artists

00:01:01.390 --> 00:01:04.270
in the United States by the
National Endowment for the Arts,

00:01:04.270 --> 00:01:08.250
and we're thrilled to have
actually not just two;

00:01:08.250 --> 00:01:14.540
we have three here today with
us, and that's very exciting.

00:01:14.540 --> 00:01:19.600
All the way from California,
we Roy and PJ Hirabayashi,

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:26.240
the leaders of San Jose Taiko,
and we have Daniel Sheehy,

00:01:26.240 --> 00:01:31.010
the Ethno Music College's Director
Emeritus of Smithsonian Folkways,

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:35.700
and actually, a National
Endowment Heritage Fellow

00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:37.190
for Cultural Advocacy.

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:41.240
So, he's going to be doing some of
this cultural advocacy work today,

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:44.100
interviewing our artists here.

00:01:44.100 --> 00:01:48.060
Just as a little bit of background
the Homegrown Series is an

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:51.470
opportunity for the American
Folklife Center to work

00:01:51.470 --> 00:01:55.030
with cultural specialists
folklorists at the Music colleges,

00:01:55.030 --> 00:01:59.430
artists around the country
to identify the very best

00:01:59.430 --> 00:02:04.570
of traditional arts, music,
dance, narrative, arts,

00:02:04.570 --> 00:02:07.420
and work with individuals
to bring artists here

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:13.560
to share their traditions with
all of you and to consent,

00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:17.160
agree to be recorded
for our archives.

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:19.180
And this session today
is no different.

00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:24.510 position:56%
It will be recorded, and this
conversation will be in our archives

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:28.090
so that future generations
can access it,

00:02:28.090 --> 00:02:32.140
and people around the world will
be able to view and listen to it.

00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:37.680 position:56%
So, with that little caveat, let me
ask you to turn off your cell phone,

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:42.060
if you have such a
thing and have it on,

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:46.200
or else you will memorialized
in our archive as well.

00:02:48.450 --> 00:02:53.930
I also want to thank,
actually, while I'm on the topic

00:02:53.930 --> 00:02:58.660
of acknowledgements and
talking about partners

00:02:58.660 --> 00:03:02.680 position:56%
and individuals we work with, I
also want to thank Mark Rooney today

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:05.580
of Washington, DC,
who was very gracious,

00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:09.470
for learning his drums today

00:03:09.470 --> 00:03:14.250
because I believe the
San Jose Taiko Drums are

00:03:14.250 --> 00:03:18.570
over on the mall right now
and need to stay there.

00:03:18.570 --> 00:03:25.180
So, but at any rate, so our
program today, acknowledged as one

00:03:25.180 --> 00:03:28.480
of the Premiere Music
Ensembles in the United States,

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:34.850
San Jose Taiko was founded in 1973
by young Asian Americans searching

00:03:34.850 --> 00:03:39.770
to convey their experiences as
third generation Japanese Americans

00:03:39.770 --> 00:03:42.850
and inspired by traditional
Japanese drumming.

00:03:42.850 --> 00:03:45.660
Company performers express
the beauty and harmony

00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:49.400
of the human spirit through
the voice of the Taiko drum,

00:03:49.400 --> 00:03:54.510
and as they strive to create new
dimensions in music, movement,

00:03:54.510 --> 00:03:59.460 position:56%
and tradition, San Jose Taiko's
performances feature visual elements

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:02.570
in choreography requiring
physical strength,

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:05.310
endurance, focus, and energy.

00:04:05.310 --> 00:04:08.200
And the members of the group
participate in composing,

00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:12.280
choreographing, designing,
and fabricating costumes

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:14.370
and hand crafting the drums.

00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:17.240
This collective effort
produces a performance

00:04:17.240 --> 00:04:20.260
that highlights group
unity and purpose.

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:23.650
In 1987, San Jose Taiko became one

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:26.490
of the first American
Taiko ensembles

00:04:26.490 --> 00:04:28.990
to be invited to perform in Japan.

00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:31.550
They have performed in
a wide range of venues,

00:04:31.550 --> 00:04:36.720
from small community
centers throughout California

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:39.460
and schools, to Carnegie Hall.

00:04:39.460 --> 00:04:43.170
In addition to offering
extensive educational

00:04:43.170 --> 00:04:47.530
and community outreach programs,
San Jose Taiko is currently working

00:04:47.530 --> 00:04:51.180
on establishing a Taiko
Conservatory, the first of its kind

00:04:51.180 --> 00:04:53.320
in the United States,
which is exciting.

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:55.350
I hope we'll hear more about that.

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:59.350
Roy and PJ are credited for
developing a holistic art form

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:01.390
that embraces artistic excellence,

00:05:01.390 --> 00:05:04.700
while also encouraging
San Jose Taiko members

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:07.130
to become leaders and
community builders.

00:05:07.130 --> 00:05:10.390
So, please, let's welcome
Roy and PJ Hirabayashi,

00:05:10.390 --> 00:05:12.510
National Heritage Fellows,
