it was a search of identity,

00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:06.640
asking the question of
what is my heritage,

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:10.960
what is my ethnic background,
where do my family,

00:07:10.960 --> 00:07:16.050
where does my family come from,
and how do we fit here in America.

00:07:16.050 --> 00:07:20.510
I'm Sansei, third generation; so,
my grandparents emigrated here

00:07:20.510 --> 00:07:22.700
from Japan, from Hiroshima
[phonetic] area.

00:07:22.700 --> 00:07:25.330
My parents were born here
in the United States,

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:29.400
but they were actually sent back to
Japan to be raised from elementary

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:31.610
to high school, and then came back

00:07:31.610 --> 00:07:34.320
to the US just before
World War II broke out.

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:37.510
So, they were primary Japanese
speaking when they returned

00:07:37.510 --> 00:07:39.900
to the US, so they're
considered what's called,

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:43.180 position:56%
they're Nisei second generation, but
they're considered Kepay [phonetic],

00:07:43.180 --> 00:07:46.190
raised in Japan but
American citizens.

00:07:46.190 --> 00:07:50.210
Sansei, I was born right after
World War II in the early 1950's,

00:07:50.210 --> 00:07:53.730
and so at that time for us,
for me, it was really kind

00:07:53.730 --> 00:07:55.030
of the search of who I was.

00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:58.470
I was a Japanese American,
and within that context

00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:01.150
of what was going on
again in the late 1960s.

00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:04.240
That was the beginning of
Ethnic Studies on campuses.

00:08:04.240 --> 00:08:07.960 position:56%
Again, the Anti-War Movement was
going on, the war in Southeast Asia;

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:12.700
so, for a lot of us, it was just
trying to search how that identity

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:14.000
or search for what we were

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.910
as Japanese Americans was
really kind of what's going on.

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:22.270
And so, I've always loved music,
playing music in different ways,

00:08:22.270 --> 00:08:25.190
and so when I discovered the
Taiko, the Japanese drum,

00:08:25.190 --> 00:08:30.520
I quickly discovered or found that
this was a voice that was missing

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:34.120
in my life because growing up
there was no musical voice for me

00:08:34.120 --> 00:08:37.610
that really connected to my
heritage as a Japanese American..

00:08:37.610 --> 00:08:38.910
PJ can answer that.

00:08:38.910 --> 00:08:41.890
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Can I just ask
