00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:43.000
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi:
Well, first of all,

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.900
Taiko is the Japanese word
for the Japanese drum.

00:17:44.900 --> 00:17:48.350
So, it refers to all the different
size drums you actually will see

00:17:48.350 --> 00:17:50.370
in Japan or here in
the United States now,

00:17:50.370 --> 00:17:52.900
and actually you could see just
from our small collection here

00:17:52.900 --> 00:17:54.920
that we're using there's a variety

00:17:54.920 --> 00:17:57.100
of different styles
that the drum comes in.

00:17:57.100 --> 00:18:00.770
And as I mentioned before,
they actually be much larger.

00:18:00.770 --> 00:18:03.850
In Japan, or even here in the US,
you'll see drums sort of up to four

00:18:03.850 --> 00:18:06.660
or five feet in diameter,
weighing 3, 4,

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:09.150 position:56%
500 pounds to this much smaller drum

00:18:09.150 --> 00:18:11.230
that can actually be
held in one hand.

00:18:11.230 --> 00:18:13.440
And so, what we have in collection

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:16.200
in general is the barrel
style Taiko,

00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:18.890
which they call the Narvado
[phonetic] drum, See,

00:18:18.890 --> 00:18:22.320
it's tacked on with tacks in
order to put the cowhide on there,

00:18:22.320 --> 00:18:25.970 position:56%
and the smaller drums, the real
small drum, we call the Shime Taiko.

00:18:25.970 --> 00:18:29.750
It's double-headed with rope,
and you could adjust the tension

00:18:29.750 --> 00:18:31.170
and the pitch with the rope,

00:18:31.170 --> 00:18:33.990
and then the little bit longer
barrel drum in the middle,

00:18:33.990 --> 00:18:36.610
we call kettle drum, which
is also barrel style,

00:18:36.610 --> 00:18:38.150
made out of flat woods.

00:18:38.150 --> 00:18:42.850
And those drums also are tied by
rope with the different heads.

00:18:42.850 --> 00:18:45.650
And those, those kettles, also
come in many different sizes,

00:18:45.650 --> 00:18:48.420
much smaller ones that you
carry around to larger ones

00:18:48.420 --> 00:18:50.050
that would sit on a stand.

00:18:50.050 --> 00:18:53.830
But in Japan, again, or here in
the United States, we use a variety

00:18:53.830 --> 00:18:56.120
of different drums in order to
create the different pitches,

00:18:56.120 --> 00:18:59.830
styles, uses within
movement or dance also,

00:18:59.830 --> 00:19:03.980
and in order to really create the
music that we want to be doing.

00:19:03.980 --> 00:19:06.280 position:56%
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: So, maybe what
we can explain is what you're seeing

00:19:06.280 --> 00:19:08.390
today as kind of contemporary.

00:19:08.390 --> 00:19:14.540
So, what we've been able to infuse
in our style is some understanding

00:19:14.540 --> 00:19:18.740
and respect for the roots of
where Taiko come from, from Japan.

00:19:18.740 --> 00:19:22.890
And in Japan, Taiko
was really never used

00:19:22.890 --> 00:19:27.220
for art sake; it was for life sake.

00:19:27.220 --> 00:19:32.090
It's to accompany the prayers and
chanting for good harvest and rain,

00:19:32.090 --> 00:19:40.510
and also to chase away
the insects from crops,

00:19:40.510 --> 00:19:47.510
and in time of bountiful
harvest there was celebration;

00:19:47.510 --> 00:19:50.050
so, for a good harvest.

00:19:50.050 --> 00:19:54.210
Even warriors would use the sound
of Taiko to frighten their enemy.

00:19:54.210 --> 00:19:59.670 position:56%
The villagers would use Taiko to
have people congregate in the center

00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:05.230
of the village when there
was a time to come together.

00:20:05.230 --> 00:20:10.200
But Kumi-daiko, K-u-m-i, in
Japanese it means "ensemble."

00:20:10.200 --> 00:20:13.590
Ensemble playing really
did not become popular

00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:18.520
until after World War II,
and I think this is all

00:20:18.520 --> 00:20:23.210
from the same reason like why we
play joyfully for a celebration.

00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:28.250
This is after World War II, and in
Japan there were some Taiko players

00:20:28.250 --> 00:20:32.650
that they felt that, wow, we need
to kind of reinvigorate to become,

00:20:32.650 --> 00:20:38.740
you know, enliven, uplift ourselves
for after a harsh World War,

00:20:38.740 --> 00:20:44.290
and that's how Kumi-daiko started
to become popular in Japan.

00:20:44.290 --> 00:20:48.400
So, it's, we're not talking
about ancient Kumi-daiko playing.

00:20:48.400 --> 00:20:51.340
So, that's what really
infused our interest.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:55.900
Like how do we use this as a
tool of bringing people together,

00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:59.090
building community,
and like expression?

00:20:59.090 --> 00:21:01.670
There was no way.

00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:03.110
Remember, when we started a group

00:21:03.110 --> 00:21:08.270
in the 1970's we didn't have any
cell phones or computers, so LPs,

00:21:08.270 --> 00:21:14.240
you know, we would buy these
LPs from Japan and play it;

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:18.010
and yet there was something
about it that we felt that, wow,

00:21:18.010 --> 00:21:21.760
let's recognize these rich
traditions from Japan,

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:24.000
but let's just don't copy.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.620
You know, we just don't want to
copy or appropriate those songs.

00:21:27.620 --> 00:21:32.490
Let's create music that comes
from us, you know, and let's also,

00:21:32.490 --> 00:21:37.340
we didn't, we couldn't afford
drums -- quickly going back,

00:21:37.340 --> 00:21:42.200
we didn't afford drums from Japan
because one small drum would cost

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:47.760
like $3000 to $5000 just
for a group to have.

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:50.520
So, one of our predecessor groups,

00:21:50.520 --> 00:21:55.080
Sansei Taiko down in Los
Angeles, was very innovative.

00:21:55.080 --> 00:22:02.350
They took a wine barrel that they
bought in Los Angeles and wanted

00:22:02.350 --> 00:22:07.900 position:56%
to make Taiko become accessible like
more through the Buddhist Temple

00:22:07.900 --> 00:22:12.270
and activities to draw in young
people because there was kind

00:22:12.270 --> 00:22:16.640
of like young people were losing
interest in Buddhist religion.

00:22:16.640 --> 00:22:18.950
So, Sansei Taiko,

00:22:18.950 --> 00:22:20.250
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: Kinnaro.

00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:22.300
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi:
Kinnaro Taiko, excuse me,

00:22:22.300 --> 00:22:30.930
devised these wine barrel Taiko,
which actually is the predecessor

00:22:30.930 --> 00:22:35.750
of American Taiko, and
that's what you see here.

00:22:35.750 --> 00:22:37.340
It's actually a combination.

00:22:37.340 --> 00:22:41.090
I think there's two drums, the
small pitch drums that are roped

00:22:41.090 --> 00:22:44.850
from Japan, and the other three
drums are actually made here

00:22:44.850 --> 00:22:46.390
in the States.

00:22:46.390 --> 00:22:49.220
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: So, if you
had your full group here,

00:22:49.220 --> 00:22:53.750
here we have one, two, three,
four, five drums, two players,

00:22:53.750 --> 00:22:57.060
how many drums and how many
people would we have here

00:22:57.060 --> 00:22:59.460
for a typical San Jose Taiko?

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:00.790
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: For San
Jose Taiko, I think we have

00:23:00.790 --> 00:23:03.230
about 22 performing members.

00:23:03.230 --> 00:23:07.460
There's occasions at home where
we'll play with all members

00:23:07.460 --> 00:23:11.320
and actually fill up an
entire room out on the stage,

00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:13.480
and so, and a variety of drums.

00:23:13.480 --> 00:23:15.290
So, when we tour, actually,

00:23:15.290 --> 00:23:20.310
we're touring with a good almost 20
different drums of different sizes

00:23:20.310 --> 00:23:22.990
in order to do one
performance concert.

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:27.950
There's a base, I guess, style
or ensemble drum, which is about,

00:23:27.950 --> 00:23:30.700
I guess, about 10 pieces
minimum that we would use,

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:32.900
but they're much larger
than what we have here.

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:34.200
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Mm-hmm.

00:23:34.200 --> 00:23:35.780
Okay. Yeah, I was wondering
about that

00:23:35.780 --> 00:23:38.090
because I thought I could hear
the [inaudible] Stradivarius

00:23:38.090 --> 00:23:39.390
Strings resonating.

00:23:39.390 --> 00:23:40.690
[Laughing] Okay.

00:23:40.690 --> 00:23:42.910
I just wondered if we
have like 10 more drums,

00:23:42.910 --> 00:23:46.350
what would happen to
the glass over there.

00:23:46.350 --> 00:23:53.730
So, help us out here, so when
we're listening to you all perform,

00:23:53.730 --> 00:23:57.560
or San Jose Taiko perform, what
should we pay attention to?

00:23:57.560 --> 00:23:59.200 position:56%
I mean, obviously, there's movement.

00:23:59.200 --> 00:24:01.080
There's a visual aspect there.

00:24:01.080 --> 00:24:04.920
There's sound, there's
quite a bit going on.

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:08.390 position:56%
Give us something to grab onto here.

00:24:08.390 --> 00:24:13.990
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: Well, I
would say, as a viewer audience,

00:24:13.990 --> 00:24:18.250
just listen with open
mind and open heart.

00:24:18.250 --> 00:24:25.080
Don't categorize us as saying,
that's not authentic from Japan.

00:24:25.080 --> 00:24:32.900 position:56%
And I think also what we really want
to have people experience is kind

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:38.920
of finding your own story, how
in our explanation of the songs

00:24:38.920 --> 00:24:44.030
that are created by individuals
within San Jose Taiko Company,

00:24:44.030 --> 00:24:48.300
there's a backstory to every song.

00:24:48.300 --> 00:24:52.760
So, you make it your, we won't
tell you exactly what to think.

00:24:52.760 --> 00:24:55.160
So, we want you to
kind of like imagine.

00:24:55.160 --> 00:25:01.340
But I really love at the end
of a performance at a concert

00:25:01.340 --> 00:25:05.270
in a theatre, and we go to the
lobby and thank the audience

00:25:05.270 --> 00:25:08.540
for coming out, we will
often hear people say,

00:25:08.540 --> 00:25:11.030
"Oh, wow, you made me cry."

00:25:11.030 --> 00:25:13.600
Or, "Wow! I'm just
feeling so great."

00:25:13.600 --> 00:25:18.150
And you go, "Thank
you, and I'm sorry."

00:25:18.150 --> 00:25:22.600 position:56%
No, but there's something about
that experience that you touch them.

00:25:22.600 --> 00:25:25.130
You know, if there was that tear
that came up, there was something

00:25:25.130 --> 00:25:28.910
that they were able to experience.

00:25:28.910 --> 00:25:30.660
So, it's kind of like, yeah,

00:25:30.660 --> 00:25:33.420
we leave it out for the
expression to speak for itself.

00:25:33.420 --> 00:25:34.720
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: We're
like that people got to decide

00:25:34.720 --> 00:25:37.010
for themselves what they want to
take from it without a certain,

00:25:37.010 --> 00:25:39.520
being guided in a certain
direction, right.

00:25:39.520 --> 00:25:41.590
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: I do say
that like in the philosophy

00:25:41.590 --> 00:25:44.100
of San Jose Taiko that
there is purpose

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:47.590
and intention behind
everything that we do,

00:25:47.590 --> 00:25:52.380
and even though we don't tell you,
it's a little way through our,

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:56.500
you know, selves that we're
communicating, you know, this,

00:25:56.500 --> 00:26:01.470
the principles of playing
together as an ensemble of oneness,

00:26:01.470 --> 00:26:07.370
of open heart, open mind.

00:26:07.370 --> 00:26:11.060
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Bessie Peterson
mentioned that the opening remarks

00:26:11.060 --> 00:26:13.090
that I was trained as
an Ethnomusicologist,

00:26:13.090 --> 00:26:17.510
and one of the things that I
gathered from all that training was

00:26:17.510 --> 00:26:20.690
that music has absolutely
no meaning whatsoever.

00:26:20.690 --> 00:26:25.020
I mean, it has absolutely
no meaning whatsoever except

00:26:25.020 --> 00:26:27.670 position:56%
for the meaning that people give it.

00:26:27.670 --> 00:26:31.420
And I'm curious, what,
could you talk a little bit

00:26:31.420 --> 00:26:33.900
about the two sides
of that conversation?

00:26:33.900 --> 00:26:38.690 position:56%
Like what meaning, examples of
meaning that you've given the music,

00:26:38.690 --> 00:26:42.020 position:56%
either musically or in terms of that
story behind it, as you were saying.

00:26:42.020 --> 00:26:47.410 position:56%
And then, what meaning have you seen
people take from it or add to it,

00:26:47.410 --> 00:26:49.710
you know, like people
sitting here right here today?

00:26:49.710 --> 00:26:51.700
Can you give us a sense
of those two sides

00:26:51.700 --> 00:26:54.570
of that conversation a little
bit from your experience?

00:26:54.570 --> 00:26:55.870
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: Sure.

00:26:55.870 --> 00:26:57.170
I'll start with that.

00:26:57.170 --> 00:26:59.660
Well, when we started San Jose
Taiko, we're the third group

00:26:59.660 --> 00:27:03.950
to begin here in North America,
and probably at that time outside

00:27:03.950 --> 00:27:07.160
of Japan, as far as this
particular ensemble form.

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:12.740 position:56%
So, we were, as PJ mentioned, trying
to draw from experience or sounds

00:27:12.740 --> 00:27:14.400
that we felt were coming from Japan

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:16.740
but more importantly
what was we felt,

00:27:16.740 --> 00:27:19.440 position:56%
we grew up as as Japanese Americans,

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:21.520
and so the music we
were writing early

00:27:21.520 --> 00:27:24.530
on really incorporated
a lot of that influence.

00:27:24.530 --> 00:27:28.610
And so when you hear our music,
you may kind of sense of a jazz

00:27:28.610 --> 00:27:32.810
or an Afro-Cuban thing going on,
or polyrhythmic stuff happening,

00:27:32.810 --> 00:27:36.470
and so you might get that kind
of sense of a rhythm going

00:27:36.470 --> 00:27:38.850
on that you'll be hearing
when we're playing.

00:27:38.850 --> 00:27:42.580
And so, I'm hoping as a
musician, or as a Taiko player,

00:27:42.580 --> 00:27:48.020 position:56%
that people when they are listening
to us as musicians are playing music

00:27:48.020 --> 00:27:51.140
that really kind of
touches different aspects

00:27:51.140 --> 00:27:57.250
of what you may really enjoy as a
listener or just enjoy of music.

00:27:57.250 --> 00:28:01.600 position:56%
So, you might sense as the soloist
doing different things and that kind

00:28:01.600 --> 00:28:04.620
of things happening and
also different textures

00:28:04.620 --> 00:28:08.010
of what the different drums
may be doing at the same time.

00:28:08.010 --> 00:28:11.340
And so, it's really trying
to combine a lot of that,

00:28:11.340 --> 00:28:13.390
and then on top of
that is the movement.

00:28:13.390 --> 00:28:16.780
So, for those who enjoy dance
and movement, there's that piece

00:28:16.780 --> 00:28:18.220
of what Taiko is all about too.

00:28:18.220 --> 00:28:22.360
So, we're trying to combine
what we many times refer

00:28:22.360 --> 00:28:24.000
to as dancing with the drums.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:28.080
So, the audience could really
kind of enjoy that kind

00:28:28.080 --> 00:28:29.510
of variety of what's happening.

00:28:29.510 --> 00:28:33.550 position:56%
So, we're hoping that as an audience
member you're not just focusing

00:28:33.550 --> 00:28:35.690
on one person, but you're
looking at everybody

00:28:35.690 --> 00:28:38.630
and really have a hard time
watching [inaudible] ensemble

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:41.100
because each person is
doing something different.

00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:45.720
And rather than watching, say,
an orchestra or a string ensemble

00:28:45.720 --> 00:28:47.560
where it's a little
bit more stationery.

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:51.320
And so, with that, it's really
just trying to create that,

00:28:51.320 --> 00:28:54.390
the vibrancy of playing the
drum, having the opportunity

00:28:54.390 --> 00:28:58.670
to just enjoy what we're playing,
and hopefully passing that on

00:28:58.670 --> 00:29:02.020
to you too so you can enjoy that
experience too at the same time.

00:29:02.020 --> 00:29:03.990
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: It's
so multi-disciplinary,

00:29:03.990 --> 00:29:07.270
as Roy is saying, there's the
physical aspect, musical aspect.

00:29:07.270 --> 00:29:12.200
There's kind of like the
theatrical aspect as well.

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:19.800
So, as an audience, I imagine
somebody in a different discipline,

00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:23.330
ethnic, you know, art, like wow,

00:29:23.330 --> 00:29:27.590
I wonder what that sounds
like if we got together.

00:29:27.590 --> 00:29:32.530
Like I'm feeling that there's
also this inciting excitement

00:29:32.530 --> 00:29:34.090
of exploration.

00:29:34.090 --> 00:29:38.590
Even as an artist, you
don't have to be musical.

00:29:38.590 --> 00:29:41.270
Maybe it's like I want to
just experience what it's

00:29:41.270 --> 00:29:43.620
like to hit that drum, you know.

00:29:43.620 --> 00:29:47.420
And yeah, that's the invitation.

00:29:47.420 --> 00:29:50.580
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: What about
stepping back, let's say, you know,

00:29:50.580 --> 00:29:55.170
a football field, or
whatever, conceptually?

00:29:55.170 --> 00:29:58.360
Festivals, I've gone
to, for example,

00:29:58.360 --> 00:30:02.360
looking for a representation
of who is in a community,

00:30:02.360 --> 00:30:05.120
or who's in a broader
community, or whatever.

00:30:05.120 --> 00:30:11.410
And it seems like over the years
that Taiko has been selected as one

00:30:11.410 --> 00:30:16.530
of those potent expressions
that it's more than music

00:30:16.530 --> 00:30:18.110
in a general kind of way.

00:30:18.110 --> 00:30:21.720 position:56%
Do you have a take on that yourself,
or what would you see there?

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:24.160
You know what I'm trying
to, attempting to say here?

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:25.460
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: Yes.

00:30:25.460 --> 00:30:28.990
And we're excited about the fact
that, you know, we're, I mean,

00:30:28.990 --> 00:30:31.850
again, we are trying to be
serious about our musical form

00:30:31.850 --> 00:30:36.220
and what we compose, but as
a form in a musical entity

00:30:36.220 --> 00:30:38.860
that we're really trying
to build a community,

00:30:38.860 --> 00:30:41.430
so we realize that the drum
is a calling instrument

00:30:41.430 --> 00:30:43.030
for the community itself.

00:30:43.030 --> 00:30:45.100
And so, like you're
mentioning, I mean,

00:30:45.100 --> 00:30:50.450
we play for City Hall officials,
football games and festivals

00:30:50.450 --> 00:30:54.600
and school assemblies and, I mean,
weddings and even, unfortunately,

00:30:54.600 --> 00:30:56.250
funerals, we've been
asked to play at.

00:30:56.250 --> 00:30:59.780
But it's, basically, it's us being
asked to use the drum through,

00:30:59.780 --> 00:31:03.370
as a voice to call people together
and to share that experience.

00:31:03.370 --> 00:31:07.140
And so, that's one really important
thing that we feel about what Taiko

00:31:07.140 --> 00:31:08.970
for us and what sounds
like Taiko's been trying

00:31:08.970 --> 00:31:13.680
to do is use the instrument
in our music as a way

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:16.490
to help gather people together
and bring people together

00:31:16.490 --> 00:31:20.560
to enjoy what's happening
as a community itself.

00:31:20.560 --> 00:31:21.990
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: I
have to add with that

00:31:21.990 --> 00:31:25.060
that the first three Taiko
groups, of which we are the third,

00:31:25.060 --> 00:31:29.550
