development of Taiko had an effect

00:46:19.190 --> 00:46:20.490
on the preservation of those?

00:46:20.490 --> 00:46:24.190
So, can you talk a
little bit about that?

00:46:24.190 --> 00:46:25.490
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: Yes.

00:46:25.490 --> 00:46:26.790
Absolutely.

00:46:26.790 --> 00:46:30.300
Well, because I think we're just
so connected to San Jose Japantown,

00:46:30.300 --> 00:46:32.900
and our community is so
supportive of us, they go,

00:46:32.900 --> 00:46:35.770
"You're the heartbeat
of San Jose Japantown."

00:46:35.770 --> 00:46:41.200
And it's like, wow, I really
feel that the presence of arts

00:46:41.200 --> 00:46:43.850
in general, you know,
and to be a part

00:46:43.850 --> 00:46:47.790
of like all these celebrations
during the year in Japantown kind

00:46:47.790 --> 00:46:52.810
of really elevated our prominence
and exposure, our visibility,

00:46:52.810 --> 00:46:57.920
you know, that little
kids want to play Taiko.

00:46:57.920 --> 00:47:00.300
So, it's like this new generation.

00:47:00.300 --> 00:47:03.960
It's like the seeding,
right, and it's continuing.

00:47:03.960 --> 00:47:08.370
I mean, our little kids now are now
married and have their own kids,

00:47:08.370 --> 00:47:10.990
and we're going, oh, no kidding.

00:47:10.990 --> 00:47:15.810
So, there's such pride and
surprise, I would say, you know,

00:47:15.810 --> 00:47:17.710
to see that there's
kind of like, wow,

00:47:17.710 --> 00:47:23.370
I never had that while growing
up, as the silent no-esteem kid,

00:47:23.370 --> 00:47:25.870
you know, in kindergarten.

00:47:25.870 --> 00:47:28.950
Now, it's like these kids
are just like flourishing

00:47:28.950 --> 00:47:31.490
with wonderful self-esteem.

00:47:31.490 --> 00:47:33.860
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Is
this a springboard

00:47:33.860 --> 00:47:37.520
