00:49:16.710 --> 00:49:19.380
at the National Endowment
for the Arts for 23 years

00:49:19.380 --> 00:49:24.740 position:56%
as though having followed the San
Jose Taiko and the Taiko in general,

00:49:24.740 --> 00:49:30.000
I expect that this dimension
of giving to the community,

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:33.680
of thinking bigger than music and
performance was part of the reason

00:49:33.680 --> 00:49:35.910
that you were awarded the
National Heritage Fellowship

00:49:35.910 --> 00:49:37.740
by the National Endowment
for the Art as well.

00:49:37.740 --> 00:49:39.200
So, again, one more time,

00:49:39.200 --> 00:49:41.270
congratulations on
that, and thank you.

00:49:41.270 --> 00:49:42.570
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: Thank you.

00:49:42.570 --> 00:49:43.870
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: And
there's a question here.

00:49:43.870 --> 00:49:45.370
Yes.

00:49:45.370 --> 00:49:47.730
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:49:47.730 --> 00:49:50.830
I was very interested, you
know, you mentioned PJ,

00:49:50.830 --> 00:49:54.100
your background is in dance.

00:49:54.100 --> 00:49:57.400
Does someone who plays
another instrument have a leg

00:49:57.400 --> 00:50:02.540
up if they decide they want
to try Taiko, say, a pianist

00:50:02.540 --> 00:50:06.920
or a cellist, or does it matter?

00:50:06.920 --> 00:50:12.630
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: I
don't want to stereotype.

00:50:12.630 --> 00:50:15.990
But it's really interesting
to see that people who say,

00:50:15.990 --> 00:50:20.020
"I'm a drummer," you know,
trap drummer, I can do that;

00:50:20.020 --> 00:50:21.750
it's a different experience.

00:50:21.750 --> 00:50:24.550
It's like once you put the
choreography in, oh, wow,

00:50:24.550 --> 00:50:26.450
my arm doesn't extend
that far, and I can't do

00:50:26.450 --> 00:50:28.780
that many beats, you know.

00:50:28.780 --> 00:50:31.910
No, these all start
from zero; in fact,

00:50:31.910 --> 00:50:33.670
that's what we do for training.

00:50:33.670 --> 00:50:37.770
No matter what experience you have
when you come to San Jose Taiko,

00:50:37.770 --> 00:50:40.620
I'm sorry, you're going to have to
strip to zero because we're going

00:50:40.620 --> 00:50:46.720
to just layer that training
within, you know, layer by layer.

00:50:46.720 --> 00:50:49.520
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: So, part of our,
you have one more question here?

00:50:49.520 --> 00:50:52.900
Yes. We want to hear a
