00:52:33.210 --> 00:52:36.470
for all of your questions, and
you think you could lead us

00:52:36.470 --> 00:52:39.470
into what's going to
happen now with the -- ?

00:52:39.470 --> 00:52:40.770
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: [Inaudible]
I think it's important.

00:52:40.770 --> 00:52:42.070
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: Okay.

00:52:42.070 --> 00:52:43.370
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: Yeah.

00:52:43.370 --> 00:52:45.420
We're going to play this one
song actually from Japan.

00:52:45.420 --> 00:52:48.660
It's called Hutchi Jo [phonetic],
and the reason why we want

00:52:48.660 --> 00:52:55.130 position:56%
to play this is because Hutchi Jo is
this very small island off the main

00:52:55.130 --> 00:53:01.690
island Hornshoe, not too far from
Tokyo, and Hutchi Jo is regarded

00:53:01.690 --> 00:53:07.540
as an island of exile where
they send political prisoners.

00:53:07.540 --> 00:53:14.070
And yet, people were exiled
to this little island;

00:53:14.070 --> 00:53:18.500
it still flourished as
their own community.

00:53:18.500 --> 00:53:23.140
So, just because you are
"exiled" doesn't mean

00:53:23.140 --> 00:53:26.130
that you can still
find beauty in life.

00:53:26.130 --> 00:53:31.750 position:56%
So, they were able to take the Hutch
Jo drum or create a Hutchi Jo drum,

00:53:31.750 --> 00:53:37.110
or a very small drum, where it
wasn't used for art sake per se.

00:53:37.110 --> 00:53:41.600
It was there to celebrate,
where people would just load up

00:53:41.600 --> 00:53:44.740
and get drunk at parties,
and people just go up

00:53:44.740 --> 00:53:47.750
and they just play on the drum.

00:53:47.750 --> 00:53:51.520
And the reason why Roy and I really
wanted to learn this piece is

00:53:51.520 --> 00:53:53.840
because we felt that it really kind

00:53:53.840 --> 00:53:59.540
of paralleled the Japanese American
experience of during World War II.

00:53:59.540 --> 00:54:06.400 position:56%
The West Coast Japanese, people of
Japanese ancestry, were incarcerated

00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:10.510
into like ten different
camps throughout the West.

00:54:10.510 --> 00:54:17.080
And although they were there for
three years during World War II,

00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:20.390
their communities in these
camps still were able

00:54:20.390 --> 00:54:23.300
to find beauty and flourish.

00:54:23.300 --> 00:54:30.060
And so, we're playing this kind
of like that sense of freedom,

00:54:30.060 --> 00:54:34.500
sense of connection,
and finding beauty

00:54:34.500 --> 00:54:36.970
in whatever conditions, like today.

00:54:51.750 --> 00:54:55.230
So, we're, I'm personally
being challenged to play this

00:54:55.230 --> 00:54:57.850
because Hutchi Jo is
usually on an up drum

00:54:57.850 --> 00:55:01.450
like this, and it's this high.

00:55:01.450 --> 00:55:07.300 position:56%
So, if you see me whiffing at air,
it's because it's a different style.

