00:59:20.670 --> 00:59:26.870
But now, I wanted to ask
about storytelling with music

00:59:26.870 --> 00:59:30.190
and specifically with
Taiko drumming.

00:59:30.190 --> 00:59:33.440
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: Do you want?

00:59:33.440 --> 00:59:34.770
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: You go.

00:59:34.770 --> 00:59:36.070
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: Okay.

00:59:36.070 --> 00:59:40.350
So, with that context of how Taiko
can be as storytelling, you know,

00:59:40.350 --> 00:59:44.080
we've worked with performance
artists and theatre companies

00:59:44.080 --> 00:59:47.660
in that way, and so and actually,
PJ has done a lot of work

00:59:47.660 --> 00:59:50.260
with Novo Kumiamodo [phonetic],
who's based in Los Angeles,

00:59:50.260 --> 00:59:54.220
with Great Leap [phonetic], who's a
great storyteller, dancer, singer.

00:59:54.220 --> 00:59:59.130
And so, actually, Taiko can be used
in many different ways to accompany

00:59:59.130 --> 01:00:01.050
that kind of action and things.

01:00:01.050 --> 01:00:07.220
And we've been, I guess, adding
to that in different, I guess,

01:00:07.220 --> 01:00:11.460 position:56%
projects we've been doing more
recently, whether it's storytelling,

01:00:11.460 --> 01:00:14.900
whether it's sensitive dance,
like Bhutto dance, or storytelling

01:00:14.900 --> 01:00:17.740
within theatre, like working
with Luis Valdez and some

01:00:17.740 --> 01:00:19.060
of its newest works that's going

01:00:19.060 --> 01:00:21.700
on from the L. Theatre
Compasino [phonetic].

01:00:21.700 --> 01:00:25.070
So, what we're trying to do
is really how can the music

01:00:25.070 --> 01:00:28.240
or the voice of the Taiko be
added on to what's happening

01:00:28.240 --> 01:00:31.500
in that context is
something we're trying to do,

01:00:31.500 --> 01:00:33.540
and I think it's a
great opportunity.

01:00:33.540 --> 01:00:36.160
We, personally, we'd
like to do more of that,

01:00:36.160 --> 01:00:38.620
but it has been happening
for quite a while.

01:00:38.620 --> 01:00:40.890
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi:
Just one recent project

01:00:40.890 --> 01:00:44.650
that San Jose Taiko just
did, and their developing it,

01:00:44.650 --> 01:00:46.920
so it'll come out again next year.

01:00:46.920 --> 01:00:50.720
It's a collaboration of
three different groups,

01:00:50.720 --> 01:00:56.050
and it's San Jose Taiko,
the Wesley Jazz Ensemble,

01:00:56.050 --> 01:01:00.640
and also Epic Immersion Theatre.

01:01:00.640 --> 01:01:05.510
So, this is just only last
weekend that it was performed,

01:01:05.510 --> 01:01:12.350
and it was an immersive experience
where the audience were told ahead

01:01:12.350 --> 01:01:16.230
of time, this is not a sit down
concert, that you are going to be

01:01:16.230 --> 01:01:21.070
in the round and that actors are
going to be coming in between you,

01:01:21.070 --> 01:01:26.980
and we also inspire you to dress
up in 1940 vintage clothing

01:01:26.980 --> 01:01:31.180
because it was swing;
it was a swing era.

01:01:31.180 --> 01:01:32.820
&gt;&gt; Roy Hirabayashi: Big Band Jazz.

01:01:32.820 --> 01:01:34.120
&gt;&gt; PJ Hirabayashi: Yea.

01:01:34.120 --> 01:01:37.050
Big Band Jazz, and
so what the story was

01:01:37.050 --> 01:01:41.690
like Big Band Jazz
was very prominent

01:01:41.690 --> 01:01:46.770
in these internment camps during
World War II, and it was the,

01:01:46.770 --> 01:01:51.390
it was the activity of
dancing and making music

01:01:51.390 --> 01:01:56.900
that people found substance
and, you know, of living

01:01:56.900 --> 01:01:59.300
and living out their lives in camp.

01:01:59.300 --> 01:02:04.830
And so, it was really wonderful to
see how it sparked off this energy

01:02:04.830 --> 01:02:10.290
of people getting up and dance when
the Jazz Ensemble started to play,

01:02:10.290 --> 01:02:15.090
you know, and then interspersed
with the dialogue to talk

01:02:15.090 --> 01:02:20.170
about what was happening where they
had to decide and show allegiance;

01:02:20.170 --> 01:02:23.220
do I sign up or get drafted?

01:02:23.220 --> 01:02:26.880
You know, here I'm in camp,
but how do I show my allegiance

01:02:26.880 --> 01:02:30.400
to America by serving the country.

01:02:30.400 --> 01:02:33.450
So, yes, I think we're
also exploring and trying

01:02:33.450 --> 01:02:39.070
to find those ways to
really empower the potential

01:02:39.070 --> 01:02:42.370
of what our arts can do.

01:02:42.370 --> 01:02:44.350
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Well,
you've certainly empowered me,

01:02:44.350 --> 01:02:47.850
and I think a number of
people in this room today.

